<br>
An interesting point has been recently brought to my attention: Those guilds who do not reserve dates on the calandar, suffer no practical punishment for intruding on another guild's raid, as the suspension of posting privlidges for a guild that never posts, is hardly punative, or a deterrant. <br>
<br>
If the general feeling of this community is, and I think it is, that interupting someone's raid on a reserved day is still a transgression, no matter what the rules of the individual plane may be, I suggest at this time we look at increasing the scope of the punishment for an infraction of this kind.<br>
<br>
I am looking for a punishment that fits, not one that is an unnoticeable slap on the wrist, and I have worked up an idea for discussion. I also invite and encourage anyone with their own suggestions, to post here so we can talk about the pros, cons and other implications of any potential policy changes. <br>
<br>
My idea:<br>
<br>
Any guild that has not reserved at least 5 days in the last 5 months on the reservations calandar, in addition to forfeting their reservations privlidges, also loses their next scheduled rotation turn, in whatever rotation they are currently up for. <br>
<br>
Example: There are 6 Clan Bashemded in fear on a reserved day without permission from the reserving guild. Clan Bashemded has not reserved 5 days in the last 5 months (I dunno, this is an example) and they are next up for Temple of Veeshan North. <br>
<br>
With my idea, not only would they not be able to post reservations for 30 days, but they would also be forced to pass their Temple of Veeshan North rotation to the next guild up. <br>
<br>
Not, you'll note, a pass on every rotation they are up for, just the next one they would have come up. This means that the rotation they would pass for, would change depending on the time of the infraction. <br>
<br>
I feel this idea shows a committment to respecting someone's reserved day, and also that it is a punishment that would actually be punative to the group who was breaking the rules, whereas our current punishment system does not allow for those guilds who would run over someone's raid, but who do not post to the calandar enough to make a 30 day suspension of posting rights an effective deterrant. <br>
<br>
Additionally, the undesireable nature of the punishment would make most, if not all, guilds think twice before purposely breaking this rule. <br>
<br>
This rule would be very easy to follow, as the booking days are plainly marked, it would only be those who had so little regard for someone else's reserved days that would occupy the plane on another guild's booked day, or time. <br>
<br>
My .02 anyway, let me know what you think. <br>
<br>
yers,<br>
<br>
<br>
